const e={subject:"General Knowledge",chapter:"Indian Freedom Struggle (1857-1947)",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],studyGuide:{topics:[{id:"freedom-revolts",title:"1. Early Revolts & The 1857 Uprising",content:{coreConcept:"The struggle for independence began with regional revolts leading up to the great rebellion of 1857.",formulaBank:`- 1857: First War of Independence.
- Mangal Pandey: Barrackpore revolt.
- Rani Lakshmibai: Jhansi.
- Bahadur Shah Zafar: Last Mughal emperor.`,logic:"Connect the leaders of the 1857 revolt to their specific regions (Jhansi, Kanpur, Lucknow).",traps:"Assuming 1857 was a unified national struggle (it was mostly limited to North and Central India).",examples:[{q:"Who was the first martyr of the 1857 revolt?",a:"Mangal Pandey."},{q:"Identify the leader of the 1857 revolt in Kanpur.",a:"Nana Saheb."},{q:"Where did the 1857 revolt actually start?",a:"Meerut."},{q:"The symbolic head of the 1857 rebellion?",a:"Bahadur Shah Zafar."},{q:"Term used by British for the 1857 revolt?",a:"The Sepoy Mutiny."},{q:"Who led the revolt in Jhansi?",a:"Rani Lakshmibai."},{q:"Identify the leader of the revolt in Lucknow.",a:"Begum Hazrat Mahal."},{q:"Who was the leader of the revolt in Bihar?",a:"Kunwar Singh."},{q:"Between whom was the Battle of Buxar fought?",a:"British and combined forces of Mir Qasim, Shuja-ud-Daula, Shah Alam II."},{q:"Who was the British Governor-General during 1857?",a:"Lord Canning."},{q:"Identify the spiritual leader of the Sanyasi Rebellion.",a:"Kena Sarkar and Dirji Narayan."},{q:"Who led the Paika Rebellion in Odisha?",a:"Bakshi Jagabandhu."},{q:"Where was the Wahabi Movement centered in India?",a:"Patna."},{q:"Identify the leader of the Farazi Movement.",a:"Haji Shariatullah."},{q:"Who was known as 'Sher-e-Punjab'?",a:"Lala Lajpat Rai."},{q:"Identify the first woman to lead an armed revolt against the British?",a:"Kittur Chennamma (earlier than 1857)."},{q:"Who was the main leader of the Kuka Movement?",a:"Baba Ram Singh."},{q:"Identify the revolt known as the 'Vellore Mutiny'.",a:"Vellore Mutiny (1806)."},{q:"Who led the revolt in Bareilly in 1857?",a:"Khan Bahadur Khan."},{q:"Identify the leader of the Moplah Rebellion.",a:"Variyankunnath Kunjahammed Haji."},{q:"Where did the Santhal Rebellion take place?",a:"Jharkhand (Rajmahal Hills)."},{q:"Who were the leaders of the Santhal Rebellion?",a:"Sidhu and Kanhu Murmu."},{q:"Identify the person who wrote '1857' (official history).",a:"S.N. Sen."},{q:"Who called the 1857 revolt the 'First War of Independence'?",a:"V.D. Savarkar."},{q:"Which tribe led the Khonds Uprising?",a:"Khond tribe (Odisha)."}],speedSummary:"The 1857 revolt was the first large-scale challenge to British authority in India."}},{id:"freedom-movements",title:"2. Gandhian Era & Mass Movements",content:{coreConcept:"The entry of Mahatma Gandhi transformed the freedom struggle into a mass movement for 'Swaraj'.",formulaBank:`- Non-Cooperation (1920).
- Civil Disobedience (1930) - Dandi March.
- Quit India (1942).`,logic:"Associate the year and the specific form of protest (Boycott, Salt Law, Do or Die) with each movement.",traps:"Confusing the order of movements (NCM came before CDM).",examples:[{q:"Which movement started after the Jallianwala Bagh massacre?",a:"Non-Cooperation Movement (1920)."},{q:"Event that marked the start of the Civil Disobedience Movement?",a:"The Dandi Salt March (1930)."},{q:"Gandhi's slogan during the Quit India Movement?",a:"Do or Die."},{q:"Event that led to the withdrawal of Non-Cooperation Movement?",a:"Chauri Chaura incident (1922)."},{q:"Identify the founder of the 'Azad Hind Fauj'.",a:"Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose (Rash Behari Bose initiated it)."},{q:"Which movement was launched after the failure of the Cripps Mission?",a:"Quit India Movement."},{q:"Where was Gandhi's first Satyagraha in India?",a:"Champaran (1917)."},{q:"Identify the movement related to the 'Black Act'.",a:"Anti-Rowlatt Satyagraha."},{q:"Who gave the slogan 'Jai Hind'?",a:"Subhash Chandra Bose."},{q:"Which movement saw the participation of 'Red Shirts' (Khudai Khidmatgars)?",a:"Civil Disobedience Movement (Peshawar)."},{q:"Identify the leader known as 'Frontier Gandhi'.",a:"Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan."},{q:"In which year was the Gandhi-Irwin Pact signed?",a:"1931."},{q:"Which movement started with the breaking of the Salt Law?",a:"Civil Disobedience Movement."},{q:"Identify the session where 'Purna Swaraj' was declared.",a:"Lahore Session (1929)."},{q:"Who was the President of the Lahore Session in 1929?",a:"Jawaharlal Nehru."},{q:"Which movement was suspended after the Gandhi-Irwin Pact?",a:"Civil Disobedience Movement."},{q:"Identify the movement associated with the 'Individual Satyagraha'.",a:"Individual Satyagraha (1940)."},{q:"Who was the first Individual Satyagrahi?",a:"Vinoba Bhave."},{q:"Identify the woman who hoisted the flag during Quit India Movement.",a:"Aruna Asaf Ali."},{q:"Where was the 'Dandi March' started?",a:"Sabarmati Ashram."},{q:"Who was the Viceroy during the Quit India Movement?",a:"Lord Linlithgow."},{q:"Identify the massacre that happened on Baisakhi day 1919.",a:"Jallianwala Bagh Massacre."},{q:"Which movement was launched to protest against the Simon Commission?",a:"No specific movement, but nationwide protests (Go Back Simon)."},{q:"Identify the incident where Bhagat Singh and Batukeshwar Dutt threw bombs.",a:"Central Legislative Assembly Bombing (1929)."},{q:"Who gave the slogan 'Inquilab Zindabad'?",a:"Hasrat Mohani (popularized by Bhagat Singh)."}],speedSummary:"Gandhian movements mobilized millions to demand total independence from British rule."}}]},flashcards:[{id:"hf-bf-001",category:"history-freedom",term:"Revolt of 1857 (Sepoy Mutiny)",headline:"First War of Independence against East India Company rule",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Spark: Greased cartridges (cow/pig fat) offended religious sentiments.","First Martyr: Mangal Pandey at Barrackpore (March 1857).","Symbol: Bahadur Shah Zafar declared Emperor of Hindustan.","Result: EIC rule ended; Government of India Act 1858 passed.","Mnemonic: 1857 - END of Company, START of Crown."],memoryHook:"57 = SEPoys and SOVEREIGNTY shift.",likelyQuestion:"Who was the first martyr of the 1857 revolt?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-002",category:"history-freedom",term:"Indian National Congress (INC) - 1885",headline:"Founded by A.O. Hume to provide a political voice for Indians",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Founder: Allan Octavian Hume (a retired British civil servant).","First President: Womesh Chandra Bonnerjee (W.C. Bonnerjee).","First Session: 1885 at Gokuldas Tejpal Sanskrit College, Bombay.","Delegates: Attended by 72 delegates from across India.","Viceregal Context: Founded during the tenure of Lord Dufferin."],memoryHook:"1885 — HUME started the Congress BOOM.",likelyQuestion:"Where was the first session of the Indian National Congress held?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-003",category:"history-freedom",term:"Partition of Bengal (1905)",headline:"Lord Curzon's 'Divide and Rule' sparked the Swadeshi Movement",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Reason given: Administrative convenience (actual: to weaken nationalism).","Architect: Lord Curzon, the then Viceroy of India.","Result: Led to the 'Swadeshi Movement' (boycott of British goods).","Annulment: Partition was canceled in 1911 by Lord Hardinge.","Day of Mourning: People tied Rakhi as a symbol of unity."],memoryHook:"1905 — CURZON caused a regional CONCUSSION (Partition).",likelyQuestion:"Which Viceroy was responsible for the Partition of Bengal in 1905?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-004",category:"history-freedom",term:"Moderate vs Extremist Phase",headline:"Split in Congress over methods of gaining independence",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Moderates (1885-1905): Dadabhai Naoroji, G.K. Gokhale — relied on petitions.","Extremists (1905-1919): Lal-Bal-Pal — relied on strikes and boycotts.","Surat Split (1907): Congress divided into two groups.","Reunion: The two wings reunited at the Lucknow Session (1916).","Trap: Gokhale was a Moderate; Tilak was an Extremist."],memoryHook:"LAL-BAL-PAL = Large Bold Protest (Extremists).",likelyQuestion:"In which session did the Congress split into Moderates and Extremists?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-005",category:"history-freedom",term:"Rowlatt Act & Jallianwala Bagh (1919)",headline:"The 'Black Act' that led to a national tragedy",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Rowlatt Act: Allowed detention without trial for 2 years ('No Dalil, No Vakil').","Jallianwala Bagh Massacre: April 13, 1919 (Baisakhi day) in Amritsar.","Perpetrator: General Dyer ordered fire on a peaceful crowd.","Response: Rabindranath Tagore returned his Knighthood in protest.","Inquiry: Hunter Commission was formed to investigate the massacre."],memoryHook:"1919 — ROWLATT led to the RUTHLESS Dyer at Amritsar.",likelyQuestion:"Who ordered firing in the Jallianwala Bagh Massacre?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-006",category:"history-freedom",term:"Non-Cooperation Movement (1920-22)",headline:"Gandhi's first mass movement to achieve Swaraj",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Launch: Nagpur Session (1920) of INC approved the movement.","Features: Surrender of titles, boycott of schools, courts, and foreign cloth.","Khilafat Link: Gandhi joined hands with Ali Brothers to unite Hindus & Muslims.","Withdrawal: Canceled in 1922 following the Chauri Chaura incident.","Chauri Chaura: A police station was burnt by a mob in Gorakhpur, UP."],memoryHook:"COOPERATION stopped in '20; CAUSE stopped in '22 (Chauri Chaura).",likelyQuestion:"Why did Gandhi withdraw the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1922?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-007",category:"history-freedom",term:"Simon Commission (1927-28)",headline:"The 'All-White' commission that faced 'Go Back Simon' cries",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Purpose: To review the working of the Government of India Act 1919.","Protest Reason: Seven members, but not a single Indian member included.","Tragedy: Lala Lajpat Rai died after being lathi-charged during a protest.","Response: Nehru Report (1928) was drafted as an Indian alternative.","Legacy: Led to the Government of India Act 1935 indirectly."],memoryHook:"SIMON = SEVEN (members), NO (Indian) - Go back!",likelyQuestion:"Which leader died during protests against the Simon Commission?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-008",category:"history-freedom",term:"Dandi March (Salt Satyagraha) - 1930",headline:"Defying the British salt monopoly to launch Civil Disobedience",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Distance: 240 miles from Sabarmati Ashram to Dandi (Gujarat coast).","Start Date: March 12, 1930; Reached Dandi on April 6, 1930.","Symbolism: Salt was chosen as it was a basic need for both rich and poor.","Participants: Gandhi started with 78 chosen followers.","Impact: Triggered the massive Civil Disobedience Movement (CDM)."],memoryHook:"Sabarmati to Dandi — SALT became the SOUL of freedom.",likelyQuestion:"From where did Mahatma Gandhi start his famous Dandi March?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-009",category:"history-freedom",term:"Quit India Movement (1942)",headline:"Gandhi's final call: 'Do or Die' for complete independence",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Launch: August 8, 1942, at Gowalia Tank Maidan, Bombay.","Slogan: 'Do or Die' (Karo ya Maro) gave a new energy to the masses.","Response: Entire top Congress leadership was arrested on Aug 9 morning.","Underground Leaders: Aruna Asaf Ali (raised flag), J.P. Narayan, Ram Manohar Lohia.","Nature: Spontaneous and leaderless movement that saw massive public participation."],memoryHook:"1942 — QUIT India = DO or DIE.",likelyQuestion:"In which year was the Quit India Movement launched?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-010",category:"history-freedom",term:"Indian National Army (INA)",headline:"Netaji's military challenge to the British Empire",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Formation: Originally by Mohan Singh; later led by Subhash Chandra Bose.","Netaji's Role: Took command in 1943 in Singapore; formed 'Azad Hind Fauj'.","Slogans: 'Jai Hind' and 'Give me blood, I will give you freedom'.","Women's wing: Rani of Jhansi Regiment led by Lakshmi Sahgal.","Trials: Red Fort Trials (1945) of INA officers unified Indian sentiment."],memoryHook:"INA — Netaji's ARMY vs the British NARM-y (lenient) rule.",likelyQuestion:"Who gave the slogan 'Give me blood, and I shall give you freedom'?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-011",category:"history-freedom",term:"Cabinet Mission Plan (1946)",headline:"The British plan for a united India and a Constituent Assembly",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Members: Pethick-Lawrence, Stafford Cripps, and A.V. Alexander.","Goal: To transfer power and form an interim government.","Proposal: Rejected the demand for Pakistan; proposed a loose federation.","Impact: Led to the formation of the Constituent Assembly of India.","Failure: Disagreements between INC and Muslim League led to communal riots."],memoryHook:"CABINET = 3 CRIPS-y men (Cripps, Lawrence, Alexander).",likelyQuestion:"Who was NOT a member of the Cabinet Mission?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"},{id:"hf-bf-012",category:"history-freedom",term:"Indian Independence Act (1947)",headline:"The legal end of British rule and the creation of two Dominions",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],points:["Basis: Lord Mountbatten's 'June 3rd Plan'.","Partition: Created two separate dominions — India and Pakistan.","Effective Date: August 15, 1947.","Lapse of Paramountcy: Princely states were free to join either dominion.","Legacy: Ended nearly 200 years of British political dominance."],memoryHook:"47 — FREEDOM with a FRACTURE (Partition).",likelyQuestion:"Which act formally ended British rule in India?",displayMode:"briefing-flashcard"}],questions:[{id:"hf-q-001",type:"mcq",difficulty:"easy",question:"Who is known as the 'First Martyr' of the Revolt of 1857?",options:["Mangal Pandey","Tatya Tope","Nana Sahib","Kunwar Singh"],correct:0,explanation:"Mangal Pandey was executed for attacking British officers in Barrackpore in March 1857.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-002",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following was the immediate cause of the 1857 Revolt?",options:["Doctrine of Lapse","General Service Enlistment Act","Introduction of Enfield rifles","Abolition of Sati"],correct:2,explanation:"The use of greased cartridges in Enfield rifles was the immediate spark for the mutiny.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-003",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who was the Mughal Emperor during the 1857 Revolt?",options:["Shah Alam II","Akbar II","Bahadur Shah Zafar","Aurangzeb"],correct:2,explanation:"Bahadur Shah Zafar was the last Mughal ruler and was chosen as the figurehead for the revolt.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:30},{id:"hf-q-004",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Match the leader of the 1857 revolt with the region they led: (1) Begum Hazrat Mahal, (2) Rani Lakshmibai, (3) Khan Bahadur Khan, (4) Kunwar Singh.",options:["1-Lucknow, 2-Jhansi, 3-Bareilly, 4-Bihar","1-Jhansi, 2-Lucknow, 3-Bihar, 4-Bareilly","1-Bareilly, 2-Jhansi, 3-Lucknow, 4-Bihar","1-Bihar, 2-Bareilly, 3-Jhansi, 4-Lucknow"],correct:0,explanation:"Begum Hazrat Mahal (Lucknow), Rani Lakshmibai (Jhansi), Khan Bahadur (Bareilly), Kunwar Singh (Bihar).",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"match",timePresure:"deep",speedTarget:90},{id:"hf-q-005",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"In which year was the 'Indian National Congress' founded?",options:["1857","1885","1905","1915"],correct:1,explanation:"The INC was founded in 1885 in Bombay.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-006",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who was the first President of the Indian National Congress?",options:["Dadabhai Naoroji","A.O. Hume","W.C. Bonnerjee","G.K. Gokhale"],correct:2,explanation:"Womesh Chandra Bonnerjee was the first president (A.O. Hume was the founder).",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-007",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who was the Viceroy of India when the Indian National Congress was formed?",options:["Lord Lytton","Lord Curzon","Lord Dufferin","Lord Canning"],correct:2,explanation:"Lord Dufferin (1884-1888) was the Viceroy during the birth of the INC.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-008",type:"mcq",difficulty:"easy",question:"The Partition of Bengal was carried out in 1905 by which Viceroy?",options:["Lord Minto","Lord Curzon","Lord Chelmsford","Lord Irwin"],correct:1,explanation:"Lord Curzon partitioned Bengal to weaken the growing nationalist movement in the region.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-009",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"What was the main weapon of protest chosen during the Swadeshi Movement?",options:["Armed rebellion","Ahimsa (Non-violence)","Boycott of foreign goods","Petitions to the Crown"],correct:2,explanation:"Boycott of foreign (British) goods, especially textiles, was the hallmark of the Swadeshi movement.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-010",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who is known as the 'Grand Old Man of India'?",options:["Bal Gangadhar Tilak","Dadabhai Naoroji","Bipin Chandra Pal","Lala Lajpat Rai"],correct:1,explanation:"Dadabhai Naoroji was a Moderate leader and the first Indian to be a member of the British Parliament.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-011",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Dadabhai Naoroji's famous book which detailed the 'Drain of Wealth' theory is titled:",options:["Indian Home Rule","Poverty and Un-British Rule in India","The Discovery of India","Hind Swaraj"],correct:1,explanation:"Through this book, Naoroji explained how British rule was economically draining India.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-012",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who gave the slogan 'Swaraj is my birthright, and I shall have it'?",options:["Mahatma Gandhi","Subhas Chandra Bose","Bal Gangadhar Tilak","Bhagat Singh"],correct:2,explanation:"B.G. Tilak, a prominent Extremist leader, gave this famous slogan.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-013",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"In which INC session did the 'Surat Split' occur?",options:["1905","1906","1907","1911"],correct:2,explanation:"The Congress split into Moderates and Extremists during the Surat Session of 1907.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-014",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following leaders was considered a 'Moderate'?",options:["Bal Gangadhar Tilak","Lala Lajpat Rai","Gopal Krishna Gokhale","Bipin Chandra Pal"],correct:2,explanation:"Gokhale was a Moderate and the political guru of Mahatma Gandhi. The others (Lal-Bal-Pal) were Extremists.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:65},{id:"hf-q-015",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The All India Muslim League was founded in 1906 at which place?",options:["Lucknow","Aligarh","Dhaka","Calcutta"],correct:2,explanation:"The Muslim League was founded in Dhaka (modern Bangladesh) in 1906.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-016",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which Viceroy annulled the Partition of Bengal in 1911?",options:["Lord Minto","Lord Hardinge","Lord Chelmsford","Lord Reading"],correct:1,explanation:"The partition was canceled during the Delhi Durbar in 1911 by Lord Hardinge.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-017",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Home Rule League' was started by which two leaders in 1916?",options:["Tilak and Annie Besant","Gandhi and Nehru","Bose and Patel","Lajpat Rai and Pal"],correct:0,explanation:"Both Bal Gangadhar Tilak and Annie Besant launched separate Home Rule leagues in 1916.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-018",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"In the 1916 Lucknow Session, the INC and Muslim League signed a pact. This session was presided over by:",options:["Dadabhai Naoroji","A.C. Majumdar","Annie Besant","M.A. Jinnah"],correct:1,explanation:"Ambica Charan Majumdar presided over the historic Lucknow Session.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-019",type:"assertion-reason",difficulty:"hard",assertion:"The Revolt of 1857 is often called the 'First War of Independence'.",reason:"It was a completely unified movement where every Indian ruler and state joined together to expel the British.",options:["Both A and R are true; R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true; R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correct:2,explanation:"A is true (V.D. Savarkar called it so). But R is false; many rulers (like Scindias, Sikhs, etc.) actually helped the British.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"synthesis",timePresure:"deep",speedTarget:120},{id:"hf-q-020",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which British official founded the Indian National Congress as a 'Safety Valve'?",options:["Lord Lytton","Lord Dufferin","A.O. Hume","Lord Ripon"],correct:2,explanation:"A.O. Hume, a retired official, founded the INC; the 'Safety Valve' theory suggests it was meant to prevent another 1857-style explosion.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-021",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Ghadar Party' was founded in 1913 in which city?",options:["London","Paris","San Francisco","Berlin"],correct:2,explanation:"Lala Hardayal founded the Ghadar Party in San Francisco, USA.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-022",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who was the first woman President of the Indian National Congress?",options:["Sarojini Naidu","Annie Besant","Nellie Sengupta","Indira Gandhi"],correct:1,explanation:"Annie Besant (1917) was the first woman president. (Sarojini Naidu was the first *Indian* woman president in 1925).",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-023",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Komagata Maru' incident (1914) was related to a ___ that was denied entry into Canada.",options:["Merchant Ship","Train crossing","Army unit","Diplomatic plane"],correct:0,explanation:"It was a Japanese steamship carrying Indian immigrants that was turned back from Vancouver, leading to a clash later.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-024",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Arrange these in chronological order: (A) IMC Formation, (B) 1857 Revolt, (C) Surat Split, (D) Bengal Partition.",options:["B-A-D-C","B-D-A-C","A-B-D-C","B-A-C-D"],correct:0,explanation:"Revolt (1857) -> IMC (1885) -> Partition (1905) -> Surat Split (1907).",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"chronological",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-025",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which leader founded the 'Servants of India Society' in 1905?",options:["G.K. Gokhale","M.G. Ranade","V.D. Savarkar","B.R. Ambedkar"],correct:0,explanation:"Gopal Krishna Gokhale founded it to train Indians for social service and national work.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-026",type:"mcq",difficulty:"easy",question:"In which year did Mahatma Gandhi return to India from South Africa?",options:["1911","1913","1915","1917"],correct:2,explanation:"Gandhi returned on 9th January 1915, which is now celebrated as Pravasi Bharatiya Divas.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:15},{id:"hf-q-027",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which was Gandhi's first Satyagraha movement in India?",options:["Kheda Satyagraha","Champaran Satyagraha","Ahmedabad Mill Strike","Rowlatt Satyagraha"],correct:1,explanation:"Champaran (1917) in Bihar was his first experiment with Satyagraha in India, against the Tinkathia system.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-028",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"The 'Tinkathia' system in Champaran required farmers to grow ___ on 3/20th of their land.",options:["Cotton","Indigo","Opium","Sugar"],correct:1,explanation:"Indigo was forcefully grown by European planters, which exhausted the soil.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-029",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who was the Viceroy of India during the Rowlatt Act and Jallianwala Bagh massacre?",options:["Lord Hardinge","Lord Chelmsford","Lord Reading","Lord Irwin"],correct:1,explanation:"Lord Chelmsford (1916-1921) was the Viceroy during these events.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-030",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Identify the British general responsible for the Jallianwala Bagh massacre.",options:["General O'Dwyer","General Dyer","General Havelock","General Nicholson"],correct:1,explanation:"Brigadier-General Reginald Dyer ordered the firing. (Michael O'Dwyer was the Lt. Governor of Punjab).",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-031",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which incident led to the immediate withdrawal of the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1922?",options:["Jallianwala Bagh massacre","Chauri Chaura incident","Arrest of Gandhi","Death of Tilak"],correct:1,explanation:"The violence at Chauri Chaura (Gorakhpur) where 22 policemen were burnt alive went against Gandhi's principle of non-violence.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-032",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The Khilafat Movement was started to support the Sultan of which country?",options:["Egypt","Iran","Turkey","Saudi Arabia"],correct:2,explanation:"The movement was to protect the status of the Caliph (Sultan of Turkey) after WWI.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-033",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who were the primary leaders of the Khilafat Movement in India?",options:["Gandhi and Nehru","Ali Brothers (Shaukat & Mohammad)","Jinnah and Azad","Sayyid Ahmed Khan"],correct:1,explanation:"Ali Brothers led the Khilafat movement, which Gandhi merged with NCM for Hindu-Muslim unity.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-034",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Swaraj Party' was formed in 1923 by which two leaders?",options:["Motilal Nehru and C.R. Das","Jawaharlal Nehru and Bose","Gandhi and Patel","Tilak and Lajpat Rai"],correct:0,explanation:"After NCM withdrawal, Das and Motilal Nehru formed the Swaraj Party to enter legislative councils.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-035",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Hindustan Republican Association' (HRA) was formed in 1924 in which city?",options:["Delhi","Kanpur","Calcutta","Lucknow"],correct:1,explanation:"HRA was founded in Kanpur by Ram Prasad Bismil, Sachindra Sanyal, etc.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-036",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which famous robbery was committed by HRA members in 1925?",options:["Chittagong Armoury Raid","Kakori Train Robbery","Lahore Conspiracy","Meerut Conspiracy"],correct:1,explanation:"Kakori train robbery (Lucknow district) was executed to fund revolutionary activities.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-037",type:"mcq",difficulty:"easy",question:"The Simon Commission arrived in India in which year?",options:["1925","1927","1928","1930"],correct:2,explanation:"Though appointed in 1927, it arrived in India in early 1928.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-038",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who was the chairman of the committee that drafted the 'Nehru Report' in 1928?",options:["Jawaharlal Nehru","Motilal Nehru","Sardar Patel","M.A. Jinnah"],correct:1,explanation:"Motilal Nehru chaired the committee that drafted the first Indian proposal for a constitution.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-039",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Purna Swaraj' (Complete Independence) resolution was passed in which INC session?",options:["1907 Surat","1916 Lucknow","1929 Lahore","1931 Karachi"],correct:2,explanation:"Lahore Session (1929) under J.L. Nehru's presidency declared Purna Swaraj as the goal.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-040",type:"mcq",difficulty:"easy",question:"On what date was the first 'Independence Day' celebrated during the freedom struggle?",options:["15 August 1929","26 January 1930","1 January 1930","26 November 1949"],correct:1,explanation:"Following the Lahore resolution, 26 Jan 1930 was celebrated as Independence Day.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:15},{id:"hf-q-041",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The Civil Disobedience Movement was launched with which historic event?",options:["Lahore Session","Dandi March","Simon Protests","Chauri Chaura"],correct:1,explanation:"Dandi March (Salt Satyagraha) officially launched the Civil Disobedience Movement.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-042",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"How many followers accompanied Gandhi at the start of the Dandi March?",options:["72","78","100","240"],correct:1,explanation:"78 chosen followers started the march from Sabarmati Ashram.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-043",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who led the Salt Satyagraha in the South (Tamil Nadu)?",options:["C. Rajagopalachari","K. Kelappan","Sarojini Naidu","Periyar"],correct:0,explanation:"Rajagopalachari led the march from Trichinopoly to Vedaranyam.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-044",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who was the Viceroy who signed the 'Gandhi-Irwin Pact' in 1931?",options:["Lord Reading","Lord Irwin","Lord Willingdon","Lord Linlithgow"],correct:1,explanation:"Lord Irwin signed the pact which led to the temporary suspension of CDM.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-045",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who was the only leader to attend ALL THREE Round Table Conferences?",options:["Mahatma Gandhi","Jawaharlal Nehru","B.R. Ambedkar","Jinnah"],correct:2,explanation:"Dr. B.R. Ambedkar and Tej Bahadur Sapru attended all three conferences.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-046",type:"assertion-reason",difficulty:"hard",assertion:"Mahatma Gandhi withdrew the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1922.",reason:"Gandhi believed that the people were not yet ready for a non-violent mass struggle after the Chauri Chaura incident.",options:["Both A and R are true; R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true; R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correct:0,explanation:"Gandhi prioritized his principle of Ahimsa over political gains and felt the movement was turning violent.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"synthesis",timePresure:"deep",speedTarget:120},{id:"hf-q-047",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Arrange these chronologically: (A) Simon Commission, (B) Dandi March, (C) Gandhi-Irwin Pact, (D) Khilafat Movement.",options:["D-A-B-C","A-D-B-C","D-B-A-C","D-A-C-B"],correct:0,explanation:"Khilafat (1919), Simon (1928), Dandi (1930), Gandhi-Irwin (1931).",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"chronological",timePresure:"deep",speedTarget:90},{id:"hf-q-048",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'First Law of Satyagraha' as per Gandhi is:",options:["Complete silence","Truth and Non-violence","Active rebellion","Public fasting"],correct:1,explanation:"Satya (Truth) and Ahimsa (Non-violence) are the two pillars of Satyagraha.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-049",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who was known as 'Frontier Gandhi'?",options:["Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan","Maulana Azad","Zia-ul-Haq","M.A. Jinnah"],correct:0,explanation:"Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan led the 'Red Shirt' movement in the North-West Frontier Province.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-050",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which British PM announced the 'Communal Award' in 1932?",options:["Winston Churchill","Ramsay MacDonald","Clement Attlee","Lloyd George"],correct:1,explanation:"Ramsay MacDonald announced separate electorates for depressed classes, leading to Gandhi's fast and the Poona Pact.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-051",type:"mcq",difficulty:"easy",question:"In which year did the 'Quit India Movement' begin?",options:["1939","1940","1942","1945"],correct:2,explanation:"The Quit India Movement was launched on 8th August 1942.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:15},{id:"hf-q-052",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Where did Mahatma Gandhi deliver his famous 'Do or Die' speech?",options:["Sabarmati Ashram","Gowalia Tank Maidan","Yerawada Jail","Birla House"],correct:1,explanation:"It was delivered at Gowalia Tank Maidan in Bombay (now Mumbai) at the start of the Quit India movement.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-053",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who was the Viceroy of India during the launch of the Quit India Movement?",options:["Lord Wavell","Lord Linlithgow","Lord Mountbatten","Lord Irwin"],correct:1,explanation:"Lord Linlithgow (1936-1943) was the Viceroy when WWII broke out and QIM was launched.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-054",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'August Kranti' is another name for which movement?",options:["Non-Cooperation Movement","Civil Disobedience Movement","Quit India Movement","Swadeshi Movement"],correct:2,explanation:"Quit India Movement is called August Kranti as it was launched in August.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-055",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who is known as the 'Heroine of 1942' for hoisting the flag at Gowalia Tank during QIM?",options:["Sarojini Naidu","Aruna Asaf Ali","Kasturba Gandhi","Annie Besant"],correct:1,explanation:"Aruna Asaf Ali hoisted the Indian National Flag during the Quit India Movement.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-056",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Subhas Chandra Bose formed the 'Forward Bloc' within the Congress in which year?",options:["1938","1939","1940","1942"],correct:1,explanation:"Bose resigned from the Congress presidency and formed the Forward Bloc in 1939.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-057",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The Indian National Army (INA) was first conceived in Malaya by:",options:["Subhas Chandra Bose","Rash Behari Bose","Mohan Singh","Shah Nawaz Khan"],correct:2,explanation:"Captain Mohan Singh conceived the idea of INA. Later, Netaji took its command.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-058",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Netaji Bose escaped from his house in Calcutta in 1941 under the guise of:",options:["Ziauddin","Pathan Mohammed","Sikh Driver","Japanese Merchant"],correct:0,explanation:"He disguised himself as an insurance agent named Ziauddin to escape British surveillance.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-059",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who called Gandhi as 'Father of the Nation' for the first time?",options:["Jawaharlal Nehru","Rabindranath Tagore","Subhas Chandra Bose","Sardar Patel"],correct:2,explanation:"Subhas Chandra Bose addressed him as Father of the Nation in a radio address from Singapore (1944).",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-060",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"The 'Rani of Jhansi Regiment' of the INA was led by:",options:["Lakshmi Sahgal","Aruna Asaf Ali","Sarojini Naidu","Sucheta Kripalani"],correct:0,explanation:"Captain Lakshmi Sahgal (Lakshmi Swaminathan) led the all-women regiment of INA.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-061",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Cabinet Mission' came to India in 1946. Who was NOT a member?",options:["Stafford Cripps","A.V. Alexander","Lord Wavell","Pethick-Lawrence"],correct:2,explanation:"Cripps, Alexander, and Lawrence were the members. Lord Wavell was the Viceroy.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-062",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"The 'Direct Action Day' called by the Muslim League on Aug 16, 1946, led to massive riots in which city?",options:["Lahore","Delhi","Calcutta","Noakhali"],correct:2,explanation:"Known as the Great Calcutta Killings, it was a period of intense communal violence.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-063",type:"easy",question:"Who was the last British Viceroy and first Governor-General of independent India?",options:["Lord Wavell","Lord Mountbatten","C. Rajagopalachari","Lord Clement Attlee"],correct:1,explanation:"Lord Mountbatten was the last Viceroy and served as the first G-G of independent India.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"speed",speedTarget:20},{id:"hf-q-064",type:"medium",question:"Who was the first and last Indian Governor-General of India?",options:["Sardar Patel","C. Rajagopalachari","Jawaharlal Nehru","Dr. Rajendra Prasad"],correct:1,explanation:"C. Rajagopalachari (Rajaji) succeeded Mountbatten as the Governor-General.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-065",type:"hard",question:"Which British PM announced that the British would leave India by June 1948?",options:["Winston Churchill","Clement Attlee","Anthony Eden","Harold MacMillan"],correct:1,explanation:"PM Clement Attlee made this announcement in Feb 1947 in the British Parliament.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-066",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Match the leader to the newspaper/journal: (1) Gandhi, (2) Tilak, (3) Maulana Azad, (4) Annie Besant.",options:["1-Harijan, 2-Kesari, 3-Al Hilal, 4-New India","1-Kesari, 2-Harijan, 3-New India, 4-Al Hilal","1-Al Hilal, 2-New India, 3-Kesari, 4-Harijan","1-New India, 2-Al Hilal, 3-Harijan, 4-Kesari"],correct:0,explanation:"Gandhi (Harijan), Tilak (Kesari/Mahratta), Azad (Al Hilal), Besant (New India/Commonweal).",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"match",timePresure:"deep",speedTarget:90},{id:"hf-q-067",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which session of the Congress was presided over by Mahatma Gandhi?",options:["1924 Belgaum","1925 Kanpur","1929 Lahore","1931 Karachi"],correct:0,explanation:"Belgaum session in 1924 was the only session ever presided over by Gandhi.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-068",type:"assertion-reason",difficulty:"hard",assertion:"The Cabinet Mission proposed a united India instead of partition.",reason:"The British wanted to maintain India as a single strategic entity for the upcoming Cold War and Commonwealth defense.",options:["Both A and R are true; R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true; R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correct:1,explanation:"Both are true. The Cabinet Mission indeed rejected the idea of Pakistan initially, but the reason was more domestic political consensus failure than just defense strategy.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"synthesis",timePresure:"deep",speedTarget:120},{id:"hf-q-069",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who founded the 'All India Depressed Classes Association'?",options:["Jyotiba Phule","B.R. Ambedkar","Jagjivan Ram","Mahatma Gandhi"],correct:1,explanation:"Dr. B.R. Ambedkar founded it and fought for the rights of the Dalits.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-070",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"The 'Red Fort Trials' (1945) were held for which organization's soldiers?",options:["HRA","Ghadar Party","INA","Royal Indian Navy"],correct:2,explanation:"The trials of INA officers (Dhillon, Sehgal, Shah Nawaz) at the Red Fort ignited huge nationalistic fervor.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-071",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who was the President of the INC at the time of Indian Independence in 1947?",options:["Jawaharlal Nehru","J.B. Kripalani","Maulana Azad","Pattabhi Sitaramayya"],correct:1,explanation:"Acharya J.B. Kripalani was the president during independence (Meerut session, 1946).",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-072",type:"assertion-reason",difficulty:"hard",assertion:"The Indian Independence Act of 1947 was based on the Lord Mountbatten Plan.",reason:"Mountbatten's Plan, also known as the June 3rd Plan, proposed the bifurcation of British India into two dominions.",options:["Both A and R are true; R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true; R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correct:0,explanation:"The act formally implemented the partition proposed by Mountbatten.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"synthesis",timePresure:"deep",speedTarget:120},{id:"hf-q-073",type:"mcq",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who was the 'Political Guru' of Mahatma Gandhi?",options:["Dadabhai Naoroji","Bal Gangadhar Tilak","Gopal Krishna Gokhale","M.G. Ranade"],correct:2,explanation:"Gandhi sought advice from Gokhale when he returned from South Africa.",examTags:["MH-CET","CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:45},{id:"hf-q-074",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"The 'Shimla Conference' (1945) was convened by which Viceroy?",options:["Lord Linlithgow","Lord Wavell","Lord Mountbatten","Lord Reading"],correct:1,explanation:"Lord Wavell convened it to discuss the 'Wavell Plan' for India's self-government.",examTags:["CUET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60},{id:"hf-q-075",type:"mcq",difficulty:"hard",question:"Who was the English missionary who was a close friend of Gandhi and supported India's freedom?",options:["C.F. Andrews","William Wedderburn","A.O. Hume","Annie Besant"],correct:0,explanation:"Charles Freer (C.F.) Andrews was affectionately called 'Deenbandhu' by Gandhi.",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],staticGKCategory:"history-freedom",cognitiveType:"recall",timePresure:"standard",speedTarget:60}],studyNotes:[{id:"hf-sn-001",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"The Revolt of 1857",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"The Revolt of 1857 was the first major armed uprising against British East India Company rule. It began as a sepoy mutiny in Meerut and spread across North India, involving royalty and peasants alike. Although suppressed, it led to the end of Company rule and the start of direct British Crown governance.",keyPoints:["Triggered by the use of greased cartridges in Enfield rifles, which offended religious sentiments of Hindu and Muslim soldiers.","Mangal Pandey's attack on British officers in Barrackpore (March 1857) served as the initial spark for the uprising.","Bahadur Shah Zafar, the last Mughal Emperor, was declared the symbolic leader of the revolt by the rebel sepoys.","Key regional leaders included Rani Lakshmibai of Jhansi, Nana Sahib of Kanpur, and Begum Hazrat Mahal of Lucknow.","Resulted in the Government of India Act 1858, transferring power from the East India Company to the British Crown."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Who was the Mughal Emperor during the 1857 revolt?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-002",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Foundation of Indian National Congress",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"Founded in 1885, the Indian National Congress (INC) initially functioned as a platform for elite Indians to seek constitutional reforms through 'Prayers and Petitions'. Over decades, it evolved from a moderate body into a radical mass-based organization that spearheaded the national struggle for Purna Swaraj or complete independence.",keyPoints:["Allan Octavian (A.O.) Hume, a retired British civil servant, was the primary organizer behind the formation of the INC.","The first session was held in Bombay (1885) at Gokuldas Tejpal Sanskrit College, presided over by W.C. Bonnerjee.","Dadabhai Naoroji, known as the 'Grand Old Man of India', developed the 'Drain Theory' highlighting British economic exploitation.","The early phase (1885–1905) is known as the Moderate phase, where leaders relied on constitutional methods for seeking reforms.","Initially, the British administration, under Lord Dufferin, viewed the Congress as a 'safety valve' for Indian political discontent."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Who was the first President of the Indian National Congress?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-003",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Partition of Bengal & Swadeshi Movement",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"The 1905 Partition of Bengal by Lord Curzon aimed to divide the growing nationalist movement in Bengal along communal lines. This move triggered the Swadeshi and Boycott Movements, marking the first time mass mobilization and economic boycotts were used as political tools against the British administration in India.",keyPoints:["Lord Curzon officially cited 'administrative convenience' as the reason, though the real motive was to divide Hindu-Muslim unity.","The Swadeshi Movement promoted Indian-made goods and the boycott of British cloth, sugar, and other imported commodities.","The movement saw the rise of the Extremist trio 'Lal-Bal-Pal' (Lala Lajpat Rai, Bal Gangadhar Tilak, Bipin Chandra Pal).","Amar Sonar Bangla, composed by Rabindranath Tagore during this period, later became the national anthem of Bangladesh.","The partition was eventually annulled in 1911 by Lord Hardinge, shifting the capital from Calcutta to Delhi in the same year."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'In which year was the Partition of Bengal revoked?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-004",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Revolutionary Movement & Ghadar Party",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"Parallel to mainstream politics, revolutionary movements aimed for complete independence through armed struggle and individual acts of heroism. From secret societies like Anushilan Samiti to overseas organizations like the Ghadar Party, these revolutionaries kept the British administration under constant pressure through secret networks and daring military plans.",keyPoints:["Anushilan Samiti and Jugantar were prominent secret revolutionary organizations centered in Bengal that advocated for violent resistance.","The Ghadar Party was founded in San Francisco (1913) by Lala Hardayal to organize an armed revolt in India.","V.D. Savarkar founded the 'Abhinav Bharat' society and authored 'The Indian War of Independence 1857' while in London.","Bhagat Singh, Sukhdev, and Rajguru were executed in 1931 for the Lahore Conspiracy Case (killing of British officer John Saunders).","Chandra Shekhar Azad led the Hindustan Socialist Republican Association (HSRA) and vowed never to be captured alive by the British."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Where was the Ghadar Party founded?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-005",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Rowlatt Act & Jallianwala Bagh",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"The draconian Rowlatt Act of 1919 allowed the British to detain political prisoners without trial, leading to widespread protests. The subsequent Jallianwala Bagh massacre on April 13, 1919, where General Dyer ordered fire on a peaceful crowd, became a turning point, destroying Indian faith in British justice.",keyPoints:["The Rowlatt Act was called the 'Black Act' as it suspended 'Habeas Corpus' (no Dalil, no Vakil, no Appeal).","The massacre took place on the day of Baisakhi in Amritsar while people protested the arrest of Kitchlew and Satyapal.","General Dyer admitted the firing was intended to produce a 'moral effect' and strike terror into the hearts of Punjabis.","Rabindranath Tagore renounced his 'Knighthood' title, and Mahatma Gandhi returned his 'Kaiser-i-Hind' medal in protest.","The Hunter Commission was appointed by the British to investigate the massacre, but it failed to penalize General Dyer significantly."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Which commission was formed to investigate the Jallianwala Bagh massacre?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-006",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Non-Cooperation & Khilafat Movement",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"Launched in 1920, the Non-Cooperation Movement (NCM) was Gandhiji's first pan-India mass struggle. By merging it with the Khilafat Movement (protecting the Caliph of Turkey), Gandhi achieved unprecedented Hindu-Muslim unity. The movement saw the boycott of British institutions but was abruptly suspended after violence at Chauri Chaura in 1922.",keyPoints:["The movement was formally approved at the 1920 Nagpur session of the INC, adopting peaceful non-cooperation as a tool.","Indians were urged to surrender British titles, boycott government schools, law courts, legislative councils, and foreign-made cloth.","The Khilafat Movement was led by the Ali Brothers (Shaukat and Mohammad Ali) and was integrated with NCM for unity.","Chauri Chaura incident (Feb 1922) involved a mob burning a police station in Gorakhpur, killing 22 policemen and ending the NCM.","The suspension led to internal differences in Congress, resulting in the formation of the Swaraj Party by C.R. Das and Motilal Nehru."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Which incident led to the withdrawal of the Non-Cooperation Movement?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-007",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Swaraj Party & Simon Commission",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"Following the NCM's withdrawal, the Swaraj Party advocated for 'entry into councils' to obstruct the government from within. Meanwhile, the arrival of the all-white Simon Commission in 1928 unified all Indian political parties in protest, setting the stage for the next phase of the radical mass movement for complete independence.",keyPoints:["C.R. Das and Motilal Nehru formed the Swaraj Party in 1923 to contest elections and enter the legislative councils.","The Simon Commission was appointed by the British in 1927 to review the Government of India Act 1919 and reforms.","Indian parties boycotted the commission because it had no Indian members, leading to the famous slogan 'Go Back Simon'.","Lala Lajpat Rai (the Lion of Punjab) died following a brutal lathi-charge while leading a protest against the commission in Lahore.","In response to the British challenge, the Motilal Nehru Report (1928) drafted the first Indian proposal for a constitutional framework."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Who was the founder of the Swaraj Party?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-008",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Purna Swaraj & Dandi March",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"The 1929 Lahore Session declared 'Purna Swaraj' (Complete Independence) as India's goal. To launch the Civil Disobedience Movement, Gandhi undertook the historic Dandi March in 1930, breaking the salt law. This symbolic act mobilized millions to defy British laws across the country through non-violent civil disobedience.",keyPoints:["Jawaharlal Nehru presided over the 1929 Lahore session where the tricolor was hoisted and Jan 26, 1930, was declared Independence Day.","Gandhi started the 240-mile Dandi March from Sabarmati Ashram on March 12, reaching the Dandi coast on April 6, 1930.","Breaking the salt law was significant because salt was a basic necessity that unified the economic struggles of all Indians.","The movement involved massive participation of women, led by figures like Sarojini Naidu, especially during the Dharsana Salt Works raid.","The Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931) led to the suspension of the movement and Gandhi's attendance at the Second Round Table Conference."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'In which session did the INC pass the Purna Swaraj resolution?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-009",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Government of India Act 1935",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"The Government of India Act 1935 was the most detailed constitutional document before 1947, introducing provincial autonomy and a federal structure. Although the federation never materialized, the act's provisions significantly influenced the current Constitution of India and led to Congress-led governments in many provinces after the 1937 elections.",keyPoints:["Introduced 'Provincial Autonomy' by abolishing diarchy at the provincial level and introducing it at the federal center.","Proposed a 'Federation of India' comprising British provinces and Princely States, which eventually failed to come into existence.","Established the Federal Court (the predecessor to the Supreme Court) and the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in 1935.","The act granted separate electorates to depressed classes, women, and labor, further entrenching communal and sectional representations.","In the 1937 provincial elections, the Indian National Congress won clear majorities in 8 out of 11 provinces, forming governments."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Which act introduced provincial autonomy in British India?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-010",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Quit India Movement (1942)",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"Also known as the August Kranti, the Quit India Movement was the most aggressive struggle launched by Gandhiji during World War II. Demanding an immediate British exit, the movement saw widespread spontaneous protests, parallel governments, and the famous slogan 'Do or Die', signaling that Indians would no longer tolerate colonial rule.",keyPoints:["Launched on August 8, 1942, at Mumbai's Gowalia Tank Maidan following the total failure of the British Cripps Mission.","Gandhiji's mantra 'Do or Die' (Karo ya Maro) transformed the movement from a restricted protest into a total national rebellion.","The entire top leadership of the INC was arrested on the morning of August 9th, leaving the movement largely leaderless and spontaneous.","Aruna Asaf Ali hoisted the Congress flag at Gowalia Tank, and leaders like Usha Mehta operated an underground secret radio station.","Parallel governments (Sarkar) were established in places like Satara (Maharashtra), Ballia (UP), and Tamluk (West Bengal) during the revolt."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Who gave the slogan Do or Die?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-011",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Subhas Chandra Bose & the INA",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"Subhas Chandra Bose, twice President of the INC, broke away to form the Forward Bloc and later the Indian National Army (Azad Hind Fauj) abroad. Allied with Axis powers during WWII, the INA's military campaign and the subsequent Red Fort trials in 1945 significantly demoralized the British Indian Army, hastening the end of British rule.",keyPoints:["Bose escaped from house arrest in India (1941) and traveled through Kabul and Russia to Germany, and finally to Singapore.","The INA was originally conceived by Captain Mohan Singh, but Bose took its command in 1943, revitalizing it as Netaji.","Netaji gave the stirring call 'Give me blood, and I shall give you freedom' and the immortal national slogan 'Jai Hind'.","The INA included the Rani of Jhansi Regiment, one of the world's first all-female combat units led by Captain Lakshmi Sahgal.","The Red Fort Trials (1945) of INA officers Sahgal, Dhillon, and Shah Nawaz triggered massive public protests and naval mutinies."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Who was the founder of the Azad Hind Fauj (INA)?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"},{id:"hf-sn-012",category:"history-freedom",topicName:"Cabinet Mission & Independence",examTags:["CUET","MH-CET"],summary:"The final phase of the freedom struggle involved intense negotiations between the British, the Congress, and the Muslim League. The 1946 Cabinet Mission proposed a united India, but its failure led to the communal tragedy of partition. The Indian Independence Act of 1947 finally ended 200 years of British rule, creating India and Pakistan.",keyPoints:["The Cabinet Mission (1946) aimed to discuss the transfer of power and rejected the demand for a separate Pakistan for a time.","Direct Action Day (Aug 16, 1946) called by Jinnah and the League led to massive communal riots and the Great Calcutta Killings.","An Interim Government was formed in Sept 1946 with Jawaharlal Nehru as the Vice-President of the Executive Council.","Lord Mountbatten's 'June 3rd Plan' (1947) eventually accepted the partition of India into two independent dominions.","The Indian Independence Act was passed by the British Parliament in July 1947, setting the date for independence as August 15, 1947."],examAngle:"Most likely asked as: 'Which plan proposed the partition of India into two dominions?'",displayMode:"study-note",showBeforeCategory:"history-freedom"}]};export{e as historyFreedomData};
